\ul \ulc0 Maasai (Kenya)\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0
\cf0 \kerning1\expnd-1\expndtw-4
\ulnone Among the Maasai, new homes are built from time to time, most often when the family moves in search of greener pastures. They rarely stay for more than a few months in the same place. Maasai homes are oblong in shape, typically 2 meters by 3 meters in size, with rounded corners and low ceilings. They are built by women and usually when they have just become pregnant.  Construction typically takes four to eight days. First, building materials must be collected; and this involves travel to nearby forests or many trips across the savannah in search of the right timber for posts. The best branches come from the 
\i \kerning1\expnd-1\expndtw-4
leleshwa
\i0 \kerning1\expnd-1\expndtw-4
 bush, which is resistant to termites. There is one door and no windows. The structures are relatively low, in that one cannot stand up on the inside. A mixture of cow dung and clay is applied to the outside. The posts are dug into the ground close together and range from 90 to 150 cm in height. Cattle dung is used to moisten the sides of the holes: and, taking each one in turn, the woman uses a rock or heavy piece of timber to hammer the post into the ground. The poles are then tied together at the top, to pieces of wood arranged horizontally; and there is usually another line of horizontal ties lower down. To form the curve of the roof, thin saplings are wedged between the top horizontal bars and bent over to form a bridge towards the opposite wall. Saplings from the other walls are bent over in the same way and tied together with vines to form the hump-backed roof typical of Maasai homes. Smaller branches, twigs, leaves and grass are used to fill in the gaps between both posts and rafters, and the outside of the house is then plastered with a mixture of mud (made from clay and water) and cow dung -- with a finishing coat of cow dung applied to the roof. The straw in the dung helps bind the plaster together.\
